    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our lineup construction is heavily tilted toward high-floor efficiency, with **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) and **Austin Riley** (74.61) serving as our primary anchors. **Mickey Moniak** benefits from a potent combination of a 14% park boost and a favorable platoon matchup, while **Austin Riley** exploits a massive 19% SP skill advantage against a vulnerable arm in Quintana. **Brice Turang** (70.52) also warrants specific attention; while he faces a decent arm, his spot in the #2 hole and his elite speed profile make him a core contributor in our pursuit of stolen bases, which remains our highest-priority category. **Jose Caballero** (65.81) rounds out our top-tier plays, capitalizing on a dynamic platoon edge against Povich, demonstrating the specific lineup architecture we need to drive Roto value.\n\nThe tightest decision on the bench involved **Josh Naylor** (43.53), who fell just shy of the starting threshold. Despite his respectable base projection, the matchup against Ragans\u2014a pitcher with a 3.07 xERA\u2014proved too daunting, driving a 19% downgrade in SP skill that pushed him below our 40-point efficiency floor. Conversely, **James Wood** (54.46) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (55.41) barely cleared the bar, but their favorable lineup placement and positional scarcity kept them in the mix over the more constrained **Cole Young**. We are monitoring the wind reports closely for **Gabriel Moreno**, **Corbin Carroll**, and **Seiya Suzuki**; the \"Wind In\" factor has trimmed their respective scores, necessitating a cautious outlook despite their strong underlying plate skills. With **Giancarlo Stanton** and **Max Muncy** sidelined, our depth is being tested, making it critical that **Travis Bazzana** translates his elite 0.408 xwOBA into tangible production to offset the high-risk matchup against Ginn.",
